inactivity","Family history","Cigarette smoking"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efamily history\u003C/strong\u003E of cardiovascular disease is a non-modifiable risk factor as it cannot be changed through lifestyle interventions or medical treatment. This includes genetic predispositions and inherited conditions that increase cardiovascular risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options listed are all modifiable risk factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECigarette smoking\u003C/strong\u003E can be ceased through various cessation strategies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical inactivity\u003C/strong\u003E can be addressed through exercise programs and lifestyle changes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E can be controlled through medication and lifestyle modifications\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E can be managed through diet, exercise, and other interventions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the distinction between modifiable and non-modifiable risk factors is crucial for developing effective prevention strategies. Identifying those with non-modifiable risk factors helps determine which individuals may need more aggressive management of their modifiable risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Modifiable risk factors are behaviours or conditions that can be changed to reduce disease risk.","The five major modifiable risk factors for non-communicable diseases are smoking, physical inactivity, unhealthy diet, harmful alcohol use, and high blood pressure.","Modifiable risk factors contribute to approximately 70% of premature deaths globally."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61380"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17018"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61380","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61380"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T05:23:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T05:23:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9708"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75867"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:20+10:30"},"relati